			Le Cinque
			=========

A game for learning beginner Italian vocabulary, five words at a
time.  Play it at https://le-cinque.pages.dev -- buono studio!

CURRICULUM

  Five Italian words are laid out with their English translations
  hidden.  Fill in the letters to reveal all five before you run out
  of mistakes.  Over 1,500 everyday words, with spaced repetition so
  every word you learn comes back before you lose it.

WORD PRIORITIZATION

  Each round deals five words.  nextWords (api/handlers/game.go) fills
  those five slots by trying three tiers in order, taking words from a
  tier until the round is full or the tier runs dry:

    1. Review.  Words whose due date has arrived, most overdue first.
       Words you got right are scheduled too, not only the ones you
       missed: retrieving a word is what fixes it in memory, so a word
       that stops being tested is a word being forgotten.

    2. New words.  Words you have never met, taken in words.tsv order.
       The curriculum is ordered most-essential first, so beginners
       meet the core vocabulary soonest instead of a random scatter
       across all 1,500+ words.

    3. Filler.  Once the curriculum runs out, whatever you saw longest
       ago.

  Two guards apply to every tier.  No two words in a round share a
  words.tsv theme, because meeting a whole semantic set at once -- five
  colors, five numbers -- makes the words interfere with one another.
  And a word seen within SessionGap (2 hours) is held back, so a long
  sitting cannot stack a review right behind its first encounter.  Both
  relax on a second pass rather than deal a short round.

  In the English direction the prompt is the English word, so words
  whose translation is shared with another entry (PUSH is both SPINGERE
  and SPINTA) are skipped there -- the tiles would be unanswerable.

REVIEW SCHEDULING

  word_reviews holds one row per word you have met: when it is due,
  when you last saw it, and how many times running you have retrieved
  it.  Each retrieval steps the word up a ladder of 1, 3, 7, 21 and 60
  days.  The rungs are coarse on purpose -- widening gaps beat equal
  ones only slightly, and the amount of spacing matters far more than
  the shape of the schedule.

  A correct placement opens that letter across every word on the board,
  so a word can finish a round fully revealed without ever having been
  recalled.  Only words you actually spelled a letter of advance the
  ladder; the rest reset to zero and come due again next session.  The
  vocabulary count in the account menu follows the same rule, so it
  never credits a word the board gave away.
